    "# Part 4: Hydrometry and Streamflow Measurement (2026-05-03)\n",
    "\n",
    "## Overview\n",
    "The session focused on hydrometry and streamflow measurement, with Mapalo walking through core definitions, hydrometric network design considerations, gauging station types, stage measurement, and discharge measurement methods. The discussion also worked through a dilution-method example and reviewed velocity-area and hydraulic-structure formulas likely relevant for an upcoming assignment or exam revision.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Key Topics Covered\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1) Introduction to hydrometry and streamflow\n",
    "- Hydrometry: Measurement and analysis of water in streams, rivers, and lakes.\n",
    "- Streamflow: The movement/flow of water in a stream or related water body.\n",
    "- Purposes: water supply control, drainage structure design, navigation, hydrological analysis, estimating available water for supply and irrigation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2) Hydrometric network design\n",
    "- System of observation points to collect hydrological data.\n",
    "- Key considerations: variables observed, locations, observation frequency, duration, required measurement accuracy.\n",
    "- Engineering applications: dam design, flood-frequency analysis, etc.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3) Gauging stations and site selection\n",
    "- Types: primary, secondary, special, recording, and non-recording stations.\n",
    "- Site selection: suitable cross-section, possibility of installing controls (weir/flume), competent observers, site accessibility.\n",
    "- Station control: physical features affecting stage-discharge (rating curve).\n",
    "- Desired properties: stability, consistency, sensitivity, minimal backwater effects.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4) Stage and water-level measurement\n",
    "- Stage: Height relative to datum.\n",
    "- Staff gauge: visual scale for water level.\n",
    "- Other devices: electric contact, bubble, and acoustic gauges.\n",
    "- Bubble gauge: uses pressure/bubbles; acoustic: sound-based distance measurement.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5) Discharge measurement and dilution method\n",
    "- Discharge = volume over time (linked to velocity and area).\n",
    "- Dilution (tracer) method example:\n",
    "  - Upstream tracer injection; measured concentration downstream.\n",
    "  - Apply tracer equation with background concentration.\n",
    "  - Example: Upstream ~500 mg/L, downstream ~25 mg/L, background ~2 mg/L, input Q ~20 mL/s, result ~0.000413 m³/s.\n",
    "- Be careful with formula and unit conversion.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6) Velocity-area method for streamflow measurement\n",
    "- Q = velocity × area.\n",
    "- Mini-section & mid-section methods.\n",
    "- Depth-based velocity sampling:\n",
    "  - depth < 0.6 m: use velocity at 0.6D\n",
    "  - 0.6-2 m: average at 0.2D and 0.8D\n",
    "  - >2 m: use 0.2D, 0.6D, 0.8D values\n",
    "- Representative widths: use mean distances between measurement stations.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 7) Hydraulic structures and discharge formulas\n",
    "- Weirs and controls: formula factors (discharge coefficient, gravity, head).\n",
    "- Apply correct formulas and units as given in exams.\n",
    "- Hydraulic radius = area / wetted perimeter.\n",
    "- Rectangular and trapezoidal channel geometry/perimeter.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Practical Emphasis\n",
    "- Shift from theory to problem-solving.\n",
    "- Stress: memorize definitions and formula steps (dilution/tracer, velocity-area, stage-discharge, structures).\n",
    "- Continue reviewing sediment transport and related hydrometry topics as next steps.\n"
   ]
